{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":23205,"name":"","username":"Dave82","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/dave82/{size}/2369_2.png","created_at":"2018-02-11T22:43:24.518Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eHi ! After a hard work on horror style baked lightmapping i came to a conclusion that it is absolutely hard or impossible to match dynamic lights and static baked lights in a scene. In some cases works but in 90% of the situations standard lights (spot , point and directional) can‚Äôt reproduce the dark ambience of a horror game level.The best way of lightmapping a dark horror level is using baked GI + AO + Object lights.(cylinder , plane shapes) and use dynamic lights only on dynamic objects.The  dynamic shadows should be faked by either a projected blob or some sort of stencil shadows.(For references see Resient Evil outbreak levels)\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e1.Blob shadows. Unity has a component called Projector which projects a texture on a level  (There are tons of tutorials how to set up blob shadows for characters)\u003cbr\u003e\n2., Use shadow casting lights. As i already mentioned in an another topic there should be a way of using lights for just cast subtractive shadows. In theory (maybe i‚Äôm totally wrong) it could be implemented as screen space shadows.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWhat you (Urho3d devs) think about this ? Is it doable ? i would be happy with solution 1 but i‚Äôm really interested in your opinion on the 2nd solution.? Any idea suggestion/help is welcome.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2018-02-11T22:43:57.114Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":315,"reads":63,"readers_count":62,"score":1584.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":4007,"topic_slug":"alternatives-to-dynamic-shadows","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":247,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":23213,"name":"Jonathan","username":"Sinoid","avatar_template":"https://avatars.discourse-cdn.com/v4/letter/s/f19dbf/{size}.png","created_at":"2018-02-12T02:52:14.807Z","cooked":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e1.Blob shadows. Unity has a component called Projector which projects a texture on a level (There are tons of tutorials how to set up blob shadows for characters)\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eI looked into this for deferred decals.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eA)\u003c/strong\u003e Unless it‚Äôs already been changed the only obstacle there is just that the renderpath execution assumes there‚Äôs only ever 1 \u003cem\u003eforwardlights\u003c/em\u003e or 1 \u003cem\u003elightvolumes\u003c/em\u003e pass so there‚Äôs nothing to match Lights up to different techniques (\u003cem\u003ea projector is just a light with different shading\u003c/em\u003e).\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eSolutions are debatable. Multiple light passes? Lights with a \u003cem\u003ematerial\u003c/em\u003e and sort-order key? Now what about \u003ccode\u003elitalpha\u003c/code\u003e?\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAs i already mentioned in an another topic there should be a way of using lights for just cast subtractive shadows\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e‚Äì insert pedantic \u003cem\u003eyou do not subtract, because specular and stuff\u003c/em\u003e bit here ‚Äì\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e2., Use shadow casting lights.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eB)\u003c/strong\u003e If you wan‚Äôt the light to still be a real light but don‚Äôt want to render the shadow-map constantly you could tweak Light to be able to store and reuse a shadowmap instead of rerendering it every frame.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eC)\u003c/strong\u003e Or just do the render from within the editor, invert the shadowmap, and save to a bitmap to use as a gobo for the light if it‚Äôs a spot-light. The cubemap rendering in the editor already does the sort of work you‚Äôll need to do before you render and that‚Äôs all automatable. Zero the edges of the image so there‚Äôs no chance of leaks, ie. nuke seams from orbit. Bias might be problematic.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eYou‚Äôd have pretty good control either of those ways when it comes to rerendering the shadow map for changes (AMFP suddenly appearing pig masks, etc).\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca class=\"mention\" href=\"/u/sabotage3d\"\u003e@sabotage3d\u003c/a\u003e might have already done the 1-time only render thing IIRC.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe other options are pretty out there though, like \u003ca href=\"https://www.slideshare.net/philiphammer/the-rendering-technology-of-lords-of-the-fallen\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\"\u003eLotF style accumulation buffers\u003c/a\u003e or tiled cone-tracing (Last of Us).\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2018-02-12T02:52:14.807Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":2,"reads":62,"readers_count":61,"score":27.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":4007,"topic_slug":"alternatives-to-dynamic-shadows","display_username":"Jonathan","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://www.slideshare.net/philiphammer/the-rendering-technology-of-lords-of-the-fallen","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"The Rendering Technology of Lords of the Fallen","clicks":12}],"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":669,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":23268,"name":"","username":"Dave82","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/dave82/{size}/2369_2.png","created_at":"2018-02-14T15:24:52.978Z","cooked":"\u003caside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"Sinoid\" data-post=\"2\" data-topic=\"4007\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"title\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"quote-controls\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cimg alt=\"\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\" src=\"https://avatars.discourse-cdn.com/v4/letter/s/f19dbf/40.png\" class=\"avatar\"\u003e Sinoid:\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003einsert pedantic you do not subtract, because specular and stuff bit here\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\u003c/aside\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThat‚Äôs not how horror level design should work‚Ä¶How will the player (and enemies) cast shadows in a dark corner which is only lit by indirect ligting bounced off of a wall from the other side of a room ? In old horror games (all resident evil games and silent hill games) was done by the player having a blob shadow under his feet or a subtractive shadow projected constantly from a certain direction.Absolutely independently of any dynamic lights in the scene.Even RE Remastered use this trick.\u003cbr\u003e\nI‚Äôm really curious how this was done and how could be implemented in Urho3d ?\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2018-02-14T16:18:36.634Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":1,"incoming_link_count":2,"reads":52,"readers_count":51,"score":20.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":4007,"topic_slug":"alternatives-to-dynamic-shadows","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":2,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":247,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":23346,"name":"","username":"Dave82","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/dave82/{size}/2369_2.png","created_at":"2018-02-18T15:50:31.739Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eOk.So i have an idea how to do this :\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCreate a projector component with similar properties like a light that renders the character into an image from the projector‚Äôs point of view (a black background and a color value between 1.0f - 0.0f used for the character color)\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWhen the whole scene is rendered , project this texture onto the level again from the projector‚Äôs point of view using subtractive blending.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe problem with this i have no idea where to start because i still not familiar with the lower level of the engine.I could implement a projector component but there are few things that are unclear :\u003cbr\u003e\n1 how to implement this into the renderpath so i get the best performance (clearly my solution takes one extra pass to render the whole scene.Hw skinning and instancing will be handled automatically if possible ?\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe reason i‚Äôm asking this because without this i can‚Äôt do proper shadows.Just look at the scene below.How i suppose to simulate lights like this with dynamic lights ? Even if i hack out something , in the dark areas where are no lights the dynamic objects won‚Äôt have shadow.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cimg src=\"https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/original/2X/6/638d6bb5af53ed7e08e94743b28e3fc0e8ff78ee.jpg\" alt width=\"600\" height=\"450\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2018-02-18T16:34:16.308Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":53,"readers_count":52,"score":10.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":4007,"topic_slug":"alternatives-to-dynamic-shadows","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":3,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":247,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":23359,"name":"","username":"Dave82","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/dave82/{size}/2369_2.png","created_at":"2018-02-21T01:26:48.528Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eIt seems that i can‚Äôt work out any usable solution in a short time.Tried to draw a blob plane with alphamap on top of everything but that looks like crap if you‚Äôre standing behind an obstacle. Is there a way to simply turn a spotlight into a projector (subtract the shape texture instead of add ?) I tried to modify the LitSolid shader in every possible way but i always end up in artifacts or no light at all.I want something like this.(shadow under player‚Äôs feet)\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cimg src=\"//cdck-file-uploads-global.s3.dualstack.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/original/2X/4/4ab1d9dca43a5b5c3ad281bd317a6d511419a7b8.jpg\" alt\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":5,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2018-02-21T01:35:17.825Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":9,"reads":47,"readers_count":46,"score":54.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":4007,"topic_slug":"alternatives-to-dynamic-shadows","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":2,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":247,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":"downloaded local copies of images","can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":23360,"name":"Jonathan","username":"Sinoid","avatar_template":"https://avatars.discourse-cdn.com/v4/letter/s/f19dbf/{size}.png","created_at":"2018-02-21T02:11:15.447Z","cooked":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIs there a way to simply turn a spotlight into a projector (subtract the shape texture instead of add ?)\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eUse a negative brightness multiplier, also use lightmask to keep it off things you don‚Äôt want it on and don‚Äôt let any highlight producing lights near it - negative brightness will use subtract mode. Has to use shadowmaps if you don‚Äôt want it to cast past a box.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIf hightlights touch it they‚Äôll get \u003cem\u003esandblasted\u003c/em\u003e into looking awful and there will be cut-off halos around the edges since it‚Äôs a subtract blend. You still need to remove L of your lightmaps if you don‚Äôt want the negative light to burn nonsensical shadows.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIf you must mix with highlight producing lights, then tweak it to use a multiplying blend mode of the \u003cem\u003eOne-minus\u003c/em\u003e family (for 1-L instead of L) so the hightlights sharpen instead of being sandblasted down into a muddy gray mess of gross.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":6,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2018-02-21T03:18:38.187Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":8,"reads":47,"readers_count":46,"score":99.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":4007,"topic_slug":"alternatives-to-dynamic-shadows","display_username":"Jonathan","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":3}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":669,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":true},{"id":23361,"name":"","username":"Dave82","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/dave82/{size}/2369_2.png","created_at":"2018-02-21T03:23:05.676Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eYes , yes , yes ! It works ! That‚Äôs exactly what i was looking for.And without any engine modification ! Thanks man.You have no idea how much you helped \u003cimg src=\"/images/emoji/twitter/smiley.png?v=9\" title=\":smiley:\" class=\"emoji\" alt=\":smiley:\"\u003e And the coolest thing it could be conveniently combined with shadows and lights (masks).It may have some drawbacks but at first look it is perfect.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cimg src=\"//cdck-file-uploads-global.s3.dualstack.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/original/2X/0/0c3cf9895ab293c850c7c4afd89ea17245e95168.jpg\" alt\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":7,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2018-02-21T03:28:11.218Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":6,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":2,"reads":48,"readers_count":47,"score":34.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":4007,"topic_slug":"alternatives-to-dynamic-shadows","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":2,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"username":"Sinoid","name":"Jonathan","avatar_template":"https://avatars.discourse-cdn.com/v4/letter/s/f19dbf/{size}.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":247,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":"downloaded local copies of images","can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":23362,"name":"Jonathan","username":"Sinoid","avatar_template":"https://avatars.discourse-cdn.com/v4/letter/s/f19dbf/{size}.png","created_at":"2018-02-21T04:34:50.468Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eSorry about that, I didn‚Äôt realize that all you wanted was a blobby drop shadow, I thought you were mentioning them just as a reference.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003chr\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe code for negative lights happens in \u003ccode\u003eBatch::Prepare()\u003c/code\u003e for forward and \u003ccode\u003eView::SetupLightVolumeBatch()\u003c/code\u003e for deferred if you should end up needing to know where it all happens.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe drawbacks should be fairly moot if you‚Äôre not using PBR, legacy specular is usually kind of muddy anyways so it won‚Äôt be too noticeable there. For your uses you might not really care at all.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":8,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2018-02-21T04:34:50.468Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":46,"readers_count":45,"score":9.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":4007,"topic_slug":"alternatives-to-dynamic-shadows","display_username":"Jonathan","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":669,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":34815,"name":"","username":"Dave82","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/dave82/{size}/2369_2.png","created_at":"2020-01-01T22:54:34.913Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eAfter a long work and studying how Urho3d‚Äôs renderpath/shaders and graphic things work i was able to hack out some cool things that may be useful to other people searching solutions for problems described above and lot more.\u003cbr\u003e\n\u003cspan class=\"bbcode-b\"\u003e1. The Depth only pass.\u003c/span\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\nIt was an inveresting discovery that we can render objects into the depthbuffer only, Fake 3d depth in front of a pre rendered 2d background so parts of dynamic objects are overlapped by these invisible walls giving an illusion that the pre-rendered 2d shapes are really there .\u003cbr\u003e\nhere‚Äôs the result : (The whole scene including that shiny teapot in the middle is a pre rendered 2d image. The character is the only 3d element in the scene)\u003cbr\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"lightbox-wrapper\"\u003e\u003ca class=\"lightbox\" href=\"https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/original/2X/8/8c6c0529593435fdd1800f9d6eac2e63eb1f8ca3.jpeg\" data-download-href=\"/uploads/short-url/k2eheBvEVuUSgvPThPQwNbrfCJd.jpeg?dl=1\" title=\"image\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\"\u003e\u003cimg src=\"https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/optimized/2X/8/8c6c0529593435fdd1800f9d6eac2e63eb1f8ca3_2_690x413.jpeg\" alt=\"image\" data-base62-sha1=\"k2eheBvEVuUSgvPThPQwNbrfCJd\" width=\"690\" height=\"413\" srcset=\"https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/optimized/2X/8/8c6c0529593435fdd1800f9d6eac2e63eb1f8ca3_2_690x413.jpeg, https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/original/2X/8/8c6c0529593435fdd1800f9d6eac2e63eb1f8ca3.jpeg 1.5x, https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/original/2X/8/8c6c0529593435fdd1800f9d6eac2e63eb1f8ca3.jpeg 2x\" data-small-upload=\"https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/optimized/2X/8/8c6c0529593435fdd1800f9d6eac2e63eb1f8ca3_2_10x10.png\"\u003e\u003cdiv class=\"meta\"\u003e\n\u003csvg class=\"fa d-icon d-icon-far-image svg-icon\" aria-hidden=\"true\"\u003e\u003cuse xlink:href=\"#far-image\"\u003e\u003c/use\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e\u003cspan class=\"filename\"\u003eimage\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan class=\"informations\"\u003e1024√ó614 117 KB\u003c/span\u003e\u003csvg class=\"fa d-icon d-icon-discourse-expand svg-icon\" aria-hidden=\"true\"\u003e\u003cuse xlink:href=\"#discourse-expand\"\u003e\u003c/use\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eHowever the solution i used only works with the extended prepassHWDepth renderpath and there are still some things that i don‚Äôt understand why it works like it does, but in general , it works.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan class=\"bbcode-b\"\u003e2. The projected shadows\u003c/span\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\nIt is actually a hack and a slight modification of the LitSolid shader to make this work, but finally it is WORKING ! Playing with shadow and light masks we can finally get perfect dynamic shadows in a pre rendered game. Let‚Äôs see Unity does this \u003cimg src=\"https://emoji.discourse-cdn.com/twitter/smiley.png?v=9\" title=\":smiley:\" class=\"emoji\" alt=\":smiley:\"\u003e So years of testing and practicing brought us this :\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cdiv class=\"lightbox-wrapper\"\u003e\u003ca class=\"lightbox\" href=\"https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/original/2X/d/de3ef4d1462d0e26607180bec31c0ca5db508ac4.jpeg\" data-download-href=\"/uploads/short-url/vI4SFmPsPxMsmr48cC3tkfBfyUQ.jpeg?dl=1\" title=\"image\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\"\u003e\u003cimg src=\"https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/optimized/2X/d/de3ef4d1462d0e26607180bec31c0ca5db508ac4_2_690x412.jpeg\" alt=\"image\" data-base62-sha1=\"vI4SFmPsPxMsmr48cC3tkfBfyUQ\" width=\"690\" height=\"412\" srcset=\"https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/optimized/2X/d/de3ef4d1462d0e26607180bec31c0ca5db508ac4_2_690x412.jpeg, https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/original/2X/d/de3ef4d1462d0e26607180bec31c0ca5db508ac4.jpeg 1.5x, https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/original/2X/d/de3ef4d1462d0e26607180bec31c0ca5db508ac4.jpeg 2x\" data-small-upload=\"https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/optimized/2X/d/de3ef4d1462d0e26607180bec31c0ca5db508ac4_2_10x10.png\"\u003e\u003cdiv class=\"meta\"\u003e\n\u003csvg class=\"fa d-icon d-icon-far-image svg-icon\" aria-hidden=\"true\"\u003e\u003cuse xlink:href=\"#far-image\"\u003e\u003c/use\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e\u003cspan class=\"filename\"\u003eimage\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan class=\"informations\"\u003e1024√ó612 124 KB\u003c/span\u003e\u003csvg class=\"fa d-icon d-icon-discourse-expand svg-icon\" aria-hidden=\"true\"\u003e\u003cuse xlink:href=\"#discourse-expand\"\u003e\u003c/use\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIt is simply a trick using a light pass that has a multiplicative blending and in LitSolid shader i use a constant float3(0,1,0) (the normal passed in  GetDiffuse() ) vector to have the same light intensity on all faces so it doesn‚Äôt ruin the prerendered lighting in the 2d background.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWhy is this cool ?\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eIt perfectly fits in the existing renderpath. NO extra cameras , NO extra RTT !\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eIt‚Äôs not a cheap projector ! Woks fine with all light sources ! (Well there are some obvious problems with NON directional lights but can be fixed)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eVery small amount of extra passes needed.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eShadows will look exactly how Urho renders them.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eVery slight engine modification is needed (lights need extra shader param to know when to use contant normal vector).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eNice way to start the new year !\u003cbr\u003e\nHappy new year everybody !\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":9,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2020-01-01T22:54:34.913Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":37,"readers_count":36,"score":142.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":4007,"topic_slug":"alternatives-to-dynamic-shadows","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/original/2X/8/8c6c0529593435fdd1800f9d6eac2e63eb1f8ca3.jpeg","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"8c6c0529593435fdd1800f9d6eac2e63eb1f8ca3.jpeg","clicks":0},{"url":"https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/original/2X/d/de3ef4d1462d0e26607180bec31c0ca5db508ac4.jpeg","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"de3ef4d1462d0e26607180bec31c0ca5db508ac4.jpeg","clicks":0}],"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":7}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":247,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":34817,"name":"","username":"GodMan","avatar_template":"https://ava